---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import LineageContextBanner from '../../components/LineageContextBanner.tsx';
import Claim from '../../components/Claim.astro';
import FactTier from '../../components/FactTier.astro';
import VarnaJatiLocator from '../../components/viz/VarnaJatiLocator.astro';
import RelatedNav from '../../components/site/RelatedNav.astro';

// Festivals at the Vairavan Kovil (illustrative; spellings vary).
const festivals = [
  { name: { en: 'Mahasivaratri', ta: 'மகா சிவராத்திரி' }, month: 'Masi (Feb–Mar)', note: 'The great night of Shiva — central to a Bhairava (Shaiva) shrine.' },
  { name: { en: 'Masi Magam', ta: 'மாசி மகம்' }, month: 'Masi (Feb–Mar)', note: 'Festival on the Magam star in the Tamil month of Masi.' },
  { name: { en: 'Karthikai Deepam', ta: 'கார்த்திகை தீபம்' }, month: 'Karthikai (Nov–Dec)', note: 'Festival of lamps observed across Shaiva temples.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Vairavar Swamy — Kala Bhairava of Vairavanpatti — Decoded"
  description="Long-scroll page on Vairavar Swamy (Kala Bhairava) at Vairavanpatti — clan deity of one of the nine Nagarathar temple-clans, shown as a parallel worked example to the author's own kuladeivam."
>
  <main id="main-content" class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <LineageContextBanner client:load />
    {/* Breadcrumbs */}
    <nav class="mb-8 text-sm text-stone-500">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/lineage" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Lineage</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/lineage/nagarathar" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Nagarathar</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="text-stone-700">Vairavar Swamy</span>
    </nav>

    <VarnaJatiLocator highlightSlug="vairavanpatti" class="mb-6" />

    {/* Second-community banner */}
    <div class="mb-8 rounded-2xl border border-violet-200 bg-violet-50 p-4 text-sm text-violet-900">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-violet-700">Another documented community</p>
      <p class="mt-1">
        This is the clan-deity page for the <strong>second worked example</strong> — the Nattukottai Chettiar (Nagarathar). It runs parallel to the author's own kuladeivam page (Konur Kaliamman), in a different caste branch, to show how the same "clan deity as registry" pattern recurs across very different Tamil communities.
      </p>
    </div>

    {/* Hero */}
    <header class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-violet-700">
        Clan deity · குலதெய்வம்
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
        <span class="block">Vairavar Swamy</span>
        <span class="mt-2 block font-tamil text-3xl font-medium text-stone-700 sm:text-4xl">
          வைரவன்பட்டி வைரவர் சுவாமி
        </span>
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base text-stone-600 sm:text-lg">
        Kala Bhairava — "Vairavar" in Tamil — the clan deity of the Vairavanpatti temple-cluster, one of the nine ancestral temples of the Nagarathar. A fierce guardian form of Shiva whose vahana is the dog.
      </p>

      {/* Location pill */}
      <div class="mt-5 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full border border-stone-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm text-stone-700">
        <svg class="h-4 w-4 text-violet-600" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
          <path d="M21 10c0 7-9 13-9 13s-9-6-9-13a9 9 0 1118 0z" />
          <circle cx="12" cy="10" r="3" />
        </svg>
        <span class="font-medium">Vairavanpatti village</span>
        <span class="text-stone-400">·</span>
        <span>Sivaganga district, Tamil Nadu</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    {/* Section 1 — the clan-deity-as-registry idea, restated for this community */}
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        A clan deity as a registry — again
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">இரண்டாவது உதாரணம்</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone prose-editorial has-dropcap mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          On the author's own branch, the clan deity (Konur Kaliamman) doubles as a pre-bureaucratic genealogical registry: the village shrine kept track of who belonged to which lineage, one life-event at a time. The Nagarathar show the same pattern in a different idiom. Here the clan unit is not a totem-kootam but a <strong>temple-clan</strong> — affiliation to one of the nine ancestral temples — and the deity of that temple is the fixed point a dispersed banking diaspora returned to.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="green" sources={["vairavanpatti-bhairava"]}>
            The temple at Vairavanpatti is, formally, a Shiva temple — its presiding deity (moolavar) is Lord Valaroli Nathar with consort Vadivudai Ammai — but Bhairava (Vairavar) is the prominent deity here, "hence the name Vairavan-patti." It is one of the nine Nagarathar clan-temples and one of the Ashta Bhairava sthalams; the present stone temple was reconstructed by the Nagarathar in 1864.
          </Claim>
          That the village is named after its prominent deity is itself the registry logic made visible: the community, the temple, and the place share one name — Vairavar.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="green" sources={["nagarathar-nine-temples"]}>
            Each of the nine temples functions as an exogamous unit — members affiliated to the same temple treat one another as kin and may not intermarry.
          </Claim>
          Vairavanpatti is one of those nine. A Nagarathar family's temple affiliation answered the same question the Kongu Vellala kootam answered: who counts as too-close-to-marry, and where does the family come back to.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Section 2 — iconography */}
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Iconography — Bhairava and the dog
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">திருவுருவம்</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          Kala Bhairava is a fierce, guardian aspect of Shiva — typically depicted dark, weapon-bearing, and accompanied by his vahana, the dog (<em>svana</em>). As a Bhairava is classically a <em>kshetrapala</em>, a guardian of place and time, his role as the deity who defines a clan-temple is a natural fit. Strictly, the temple's presiding deity is Shiva as Valaroli Nathar, enshrined with his consort Vadivudai Ammai; Bhairava is the prominent shrine that gives the place its name. The temple carries a five-tiered rajagopuram.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-stone-600">
          This contrasts with the author's Konur Kaliamman, a village-goddess (Amman) form. Two very different deities — a fierce Shaiva guardian here, a folk Shakta goddess there — performing the same social role for their respective clans.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Section 3 — festivals */}
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Festivals
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">திருவிழாக்கள்</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-2 flex items-baseline gap-2">
        <p class="max-w-2xl text-stone-600">
          The major observances at the Vairavan Kovil. Spellings and exact dates vary by source and Panchangam.
        </p>
        <FactTier tier="yellow" />
      </div>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
        {festivals.map((f) => (
          <article class="rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-900">{f.name.en}</h3>
            <p class="font-tamil text-base text-stone-600">{f.name.ta}</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-violet-700">{f.month}</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-stone-700">{f.note}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Cross-links */}
    <section class="rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white p-6">
      <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-stone-900">Connected pages</h2>
      <ul class="mt-3 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/nagarathar" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-violet-300 hover:bg-violet-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Community</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Nagarathar</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The merchant-banking community and its nine temple-clans.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/konur" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-rose-300 hover:bg-rose-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Compare — clan deity</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Konur Kaliamman</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The author's own kuladeivam, same role, different deity.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/overview/varna-vs-jati" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-sky-300 hover:bg-sky-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Overview</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Varna vs Jati</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Where this leaf sits in the larger tree.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <RelatedNav
      readNext={{
        href: '/lineage/nagarathar',
        title: 'Nagarathar',
        sub: 'The merchant-banking community and its Nava-Kovil structure.',
      }}
      related={{
        label: 'Related lineage',
        items: [{ href: '/lineage/konur', title: "Compare with the author's Konur Kaliamman" }],
      }}
      backTo={{ href: '/lineage', label: 'Lineage hub' }}
    />
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
